  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged from efforts to combat organized crime in the early 20th century\n- Initially focused on preventing criminal proceeds from being integrated into legitimate financial systems\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (US) - First comprehensive anti-money laundering legislation\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act (US) - Criminalized money laundering as a specific federal crime\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop international standards\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention addressed money laundering related to drug trafficking\n- 1990 Council of Europe Convention expanded legal frameworks\n- Gradual development of international anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n\n4. Post-9/11 Expansion:\n- Patriot Act (2001) significantly expanded money laundering prohibitions\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing\n- Enhanced reporting and monitoring requirements\n\n5. Contemporary Legal Framework:\n- Comprehensive global regulatory system\n- Mandatory reporting for financial institutions\n- Increasing complexity with digital currencies and technologies\n\nThe legal history reflects growing international cooperation and increasingly sophisticated approaches to combating financial crimes.",
